When building fwupd-efi on systems with certain versions of binutils
(e.g. objcopy 2.46.1 from Slackware 15.1), the build fails with:

  objcopy: subprojects/fwupd-efi/efi/fwup.so: file format not recognized

Root cause:
* The build passes --target efi-app-x86_64 to objcopy to create the
  EFI PE/COFF binary from the ELF shared object fwup.so.
* The installed objcopy does not list efi-app-x86_64 as a supported
  output target format (run 'objcopy --info' to confirm).
* The meson build system only checks for EFI target support on ARM,
  AArch64, RISC-V, and LoongArch, assuming x86_64 always works.

What the patch does:
* Detects at runtime whether objcopy supports the efi-app-{arch} target
  by parsing objcopy --info output.
* If supported, uses the existing logic unchanged.
* If unsupported, falls back to pei-{arch} (e.g. pei-x86_64), which
  produces a valid PE32+ image but with Subsystem = 0 (UNKNOWN).
* Then patches the PE optional header Subsystem byte to 10
  (IMAGE_SUBSYSTEM_EFI_APPLICATION) so the final binary is correctly
  identified as an EFI application.

Assisted-by: OpenCode (Big Pickle OpenCode Zen)

diff --git a/efi/generate_binary.py b/efi/generate_binary.py
index 443472a..1b09766 100755
--- a/efi/generate_binary.py
+++ b/efi/generate_binary.py
@@ -9,9 +9,44 @@
 
 import subprocess
 import sys
+import struct
 import argparse
 
 
+# Map gnu-efi arch names to objcopy pei-* target names
+_PEI_ARCH_MAP = {
+    "x86_64": "x86-64",
+    "ia32": "i386",
+}
+
+
+def _target_supported(objcopy, target):
+    """Check if objcopy supports a given output target format."""
+    argv = [objcopy, "--info"]
+    try:
+        output = subprocess.check_output(argv, text=True, stderr=subprocess.STDOUT)
+        return target in output
+    except (subprocess.CalledProcessError, FileNotFoundError):
+        return False
+
+
+def _fix_pe_subsystem(path):
+    """Patch PE optional header Subsystem field to
+    IMAGE_SUBSYSTEM_EFI_APPLICATION (10)."""
+    with open(path, 'r+b') as f:
+        data = f.read()
+        e_lfanew = struct.unpack_from('<I', data, 0x3c)[0]
+        # Subsystem at offset 68 in optional header:
+        #   PE sig (4) + file header (20) + opt hdr offset 68
+        subsys_offset = e_lfanew + 4 + 20 + 68
+        subsystem = struct.unpack_from('<H', data, subsys_offset)[0]
+        if subsystem != 10:
+            data = bytearray(data)
+            struct.pack_into('<H', data, subsys_offset, 10)
+            f.seek(0)
+            f.write(data)
+
+
